text: Streptomyces arenae produces the aromatic polyketide naphthocyclinone, which exhibits activity against Gram-positive bacteria. A cosmid clone containing the putative naphthocyclinone gene cluster was isolated from a genomic library of S. arenae by hybridization with a conserved region from the actinorhodin PKS of S. coelicolor. Sequence analysis of a 5.5-kb DNA fragment, which hybridizes with the actI probe, revealed three open reading frames coding for the minimal polyketide synthase. A strong sequence similarity was found to several previously described ketosynthases, chain length factors and acyl carrier proteins from other polyketide gene clusters. An additional open reading frame downstream of the PKS genes of S. arenae showed 53% identity to act VII probably encoding an aromatase. Another open reading frame was identiﬁed in a region of 1.436 bp upstream of the PKS genes, which, however, had no similarity to known genes in the database. Approximately 8 kb upstream of the PKS genes, a DNA fragment was identiﬁed that hybridizes to an actVII–actIV speciﬁc probe coding for a cyclase and a putative regulatory protein, respectively. Disruption of the proposed naphthocyclinone gene cluster by insertion of a thiostrepton resistance gene completely abolished production of naphthocyclinones in the mutant strain, showing that indeed the naphthocyclinone gene cluster had been isolated. Heterologous expression of the minimal PKS genes in S. coelicolor CH999 in the presence of the act ketoreductase led to the production of mutactin and dehydromutactin, indicating that the S. arenae polyketide synthase forms a C-16 backbone that is subsequently dimerized to build naphthocyclinone. The functions of the proposed cyclase and aromatase were examined by coexpression with genes from diVerent polyketide core producers. © 1999 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. Keywords: Aromatase; PKS; Recombinant polyketides

Streptomyces arenae synthesizes naphthocyclinones, aromatic polyketides that belong to the class of isochro- mane quinone antibiotics, active against Gram-positive bacteria (Zeeck et al., 1974; Zeeck and Mardin, 1974). Precursor feeding experiments and structure analysis have suggested that naphthocyclinone is produced by two separate C-16 molecules that are then dimerized, losing two carbons to yield the ﬁnal C-30 molecule ( Zeeck et al., 1974; Schro¨ der and Floss, 1978). The genetic organization of the genes involved in naphthocyclinone production was unknown until now, and it was unclear whether the two subunits are synthesized by diVerent polyketide syn- thases and then combined, or if only one PKS is responsible for the production of the core molecules, which are then further processed and dimerized to form naphthocyclinone.

In previous years it has been shown by numerous examples that the combination of genes from diVerent polyketide clusters (mix and match) can lead to the production of novel recombinant polyketides [for a review, see Hopwood (1997)]. The scope of chemical diversity accessible in recombinant polyketides will be signiﬁcantly enlarged by the discovery of new tailoring enzymes (hydroxylases, methyltransferases, acyltrans- ferases, esterases and others) active for modifying unnatural substrates. The chemical structure of naphtho- cyclinone indicates that S. arenae harbors at least one hydroxylase and methyltransferase involved in naphtho- cyclinone biosynthesis. These enzymes are putative can- didates for the production of novel and recombinant polyketides. We, therefore, were interested in isolating the corresponding biosynthetic genes. Here, we report on the identiﬁcation, isolation and characterization of a gene cluster from S. arenae DSM 40737 involved in naphthocyclinone synthesis and the heterologous expres- sion of the minimal PKS, cyclase and aromatase genes from this cluster. 2.1. Bacterial strains and culture conditions Table 1 lists the strains used in this work. E. coli was grown at 37°C either in dYT liquid medium or on dYT agar plates (Sambrook et al., 1989), both supplemented with the appropriate antibiotics for plasmid selection. Streptomyces coelicolor CH999 (McDaniel et al., 1993) was used as the host for expression of the polyketide synthase genes from Streptomyces arenae DSM40737. Both strains were grown at 30°C in YEME or TSB liquid medium or on R5 agar plates (Hopwood et al., 1985). Thiostrepton (12.5 mg/l ) was added as required. Plasmids used in this work with their relevant markers are listed in Table 1. A cosmid library of S. arenae was prepared from chromosomal DNA partially digested P. with Sau3A1 and cloned into the HpaI/BamHI digested vector pKC505 (Richardson et al., 1987). The cosmid pKMA contains an approximately 32-kb DNA fragment that hybridizes to an actI probe ( KS/AT-CLF frag- ment). Plasmid pKM4 was constructed by insertion of from a 4.5-kb BamHI (actI hybridizing) pKMA into pBluescript SK+ (Stratagene, La Jolla, CA). A 2.6-kb BamHI and a 2.3-kb BamHI/EcoRV fragment from pKMA, both hybridizing with actVII– actIV (aromatase–cyclase), were cloned into pBluescript SK+, resulting in pKM6 and pKM7, respectively. A 3.3 BglII fragment covering part of the insert of pKM4 and the downstream region was inserted into pIC19H (Marsh et al., 1984) to give pETR398. The minimal PKS genes from S. arenae were isolated as a 3.1-kb StyI/EcoRI fragment from pKM4 (StyI ﬁlled in with PolIk) and ligated to the PacI/EcoRI-digested (PacI ﬁlled in with PolIk) plasmids pSEK4 ( Fu et al., 1994) and pRM5 (McDaniel et al., 1993), thereby replacing the act PKS genes. The resulting plasmids were desig- nated pETR361 and pETR381, respectively. A 1-kb internal BglII fragment in pKM4 was replaced by the thiostrepton resistance gene to yield pETR410. Insertion of a 1.1-kb EcoRI fragment (containing ncnE ) from pETR435 into pSEK34 gave pETR450. NcnD (EcoRI fragment from pETR480) was cloned into pSEK21 and pETR511, resulting in the plasmids pETR488 and pETR517, respectively. 2.3. DNA isolation, manipulation and transformation of bacterial cells

Plasmid DNA from E. coli was isolated either by a method described by Lee and Rasheed (1990) or by (Qiagen, Germany). using the QIAprep Spin kit Isolation plasmid DNA from or Streptomyces was performed as described by Hopwood et al. (1985). Restriction enzymes, T4 DNA ligase, alkaline phosphatase and the large fragment of DNA polymerase I ( Klenow) were obtained from commercial sources and used as recommended by the manufacturers. Standard DNA techniques and Southern Blot analysis were performed as described by Sambrook et al., 1989. DNA probes were digoxigenin-labelled using the random primed DNA labelling kit (Boehringer Mannheim, Germany) according to the supplied proto- col. Competent E. coli cells were prepared and trans- formed according to a protocol of Mandel and Higa (1979). Protoplast formation and PEG mediated trans- formation of Streptomyces strains were performed as described by Hopwood et al. (1985). Packaging of the vector pKC505 containing inserts of chromosomal DNA from S. arenae was done using the Giga-Pack Gold packaging kit (Stratagene), followed by transduction into E. coli K803 (Sambrook et al., 1989). R5 agar plates were inoculated with 106–107 spores of polyketide producing streptomyces strains and incu- bated at 30°C for 20 days. The agar was chopped up and extracted four or ﬁve times with 1 vol of ethyl- acetate:methanol:acetic acid (79:20:1). For analytical purposes, extraction of one agar plate was suYcient, whereas for puriﬁcation of a compound 30–40 plates (2 l of medium) were extracted. After prepuriﬁcation of the extract by passing through a silica gel ﬂash column (Baker analysedA Reagent, particle size 40 mm, J.T. Baker), the compounds were dried and dissolved in 50% acetonitrile/1% acetic acid and separated by preparative HPLC ( Waters DeltaPrep 4000) using a C18 reverse column (Delta Pack C18; 300 A˚ ; 15 mm; phase 40×100 mm). During the run, the absorbance at 280 nm was monitored, and the fractions of interest were col- lected, dried and analyzed by NMR and MS. 2.6. Isolation of the naphthocyclinone gene cluster from S. arenae A genomic library of S. arenae DSM 40737 prepared in the cosmid vector pKC505 was screened for putative polyketide gene clusters by hybridization with a digoxy- genin-labelled actI probe from S. coelicolor. Cosmid pKMA carrying approximately 32 kb of S. arenae chro- mosomal DNA was isolated. Restriction mapping and Southern blot analysis of the inserted DNA revealed a 4.5-kb BamHI fragment that speciﬁcally hybridized to the actI probe, indicating that this fragment probably encodes a type-II polyketide synthase ( Fig. 1). Two BamHI fragments (2.6 kb and 5 kb) located about 8 kb upstream of the putative PKS genes clearly hybridized with an actVII–actIV speciﬁc probe, suggesting the presence of a cyclase-encoding open reading frame. The 5-kb BamHI fragment also hybridizes to an actIII probe that is speciﬁc for the ketoreductase gene from the actinorhodin cluster of S. coelicolor. In addition, a 3.5-kb BamHI fragment located between the putative cyclase and polyketide synthase genes hybridized with a schC probe, a hydroxylase gene from S. halstedii (Blanco et al., 1993). Sequence analysis of the actI and actVII–IV hybridizing regions

Both strands of the 5.5-kb actI hybridizing region and of a 3.0-kb actVII–actIV hybridizing region (see Fig. 1) were sequenced. The nt sequences were deposited at GenBank under the Accession Nos AF098965 and AF098966. The sequences showed the typical GC content of Streptomyces DNA (74.5% for the PKS fragment and 70.6% for the cyclase fragment) and a Streptomyces speciﬁc codon usage, as calculated from the codon usage table from Wright and Bibb (1992). A sequence analysis and homology comparison of the 4.5-kb BamHI actI hybridizing fragment revealed four open reading frames encoding a putative type-II polyke- tide synthase (ketoacylsynthase, chain length factor and acyl carrier protein). A putative bifunctional cyclase/dehydrase (aromatase) was identiﬁed in the 1-kb downstream region. The deduced peptide sequences of the PKS genes showed a signiﬁcant homology to other polyketide synthases ( Table 2). The naphthocyclinone ketoacylsynthase (NcnA) is encoded by an open reading frame of 1266 bp starting at position 1437. Within the deduced amino acid sequence (421 aa), a highly con- served motif is located at position 164–174 containing the active site of the protein, which is common to all known ketoacylsynthases characterized so far. NcnB shows a signiﬁcant homology (70.7% on peptide level ) to the chain length factor of the actinorhodin cluster of S. coelicolor ( Table 2). As in other type-II polyketide synthases, the deduced protein sequence of the gene encoding the chain length factor is very similar to that of the ketoacylsynthase, but it lacks the active site. Downstream of ncnB, a third open reading frame (ncnC; 261 bp) is located, encoding a deduced protein of 86 aa that exhibits signiﬁcant homology to several acyl carrier proteins from diVerent polyketide clusters ( Table 2). A common consensus motif found in all acyl carrier proteins with a conserved serine residue is located at position 36–46 of NcnC. Overlapping with the stop codon of ncnC is a fourth open reading frame of 948 bp (ncnD) starting at position 4290. Its deduced peptide sequence reveals a high homology to several bifunctional cyclases/dehydrases, which act as aromatases ( Table 2; Hopwood, 1997). Within a region of 2982 bp sequenced from the fragments hybridizing with the actVII–actIV probe, two divergently orientated open reading frames were iden- tiﬁed ( Fig. 1). From position 2030 to 2962, an open reading frame, designated ncnE, is located, which shows 55.2% identity at the protein level to actIV, the actinor- hodin cyclase gene ( Table 2). The second open reading frame on this fragment, with a size of 609 bp (ncnR), encodes a protein of 202 aa, which is to 48% identical to DnrN, a regulatory protein of the daunorubicin cluster from S. peucetius ( Table 2; Otten et al., 1995).

All six identiﬁed open reading frames are preceded by putative ribosome binding sites with common consen- sus motifs ( Table 2). P. Bru¨nker et al. / Gene 227 (1999) 125–135 3.3. Disruption of the S. arenae polyketide cluster In order to prove that the cloned polyketide cluster is involved in the production of naphthocyclinone, a gene-replacement experiment was performed in S. arenae in which its chromosomal PKS genes were replaced by a resistance marker. A 988-bp BglII fragment from pKM4 containing the 3∞ part of ncnA and the 5∞ part of ncnB was replaced by a 1.1-kb fragment carrying a thiostrepton resistance gene. The resulting plasmid, pETR410 (Fig. 2A), was transformed into S. arenae, and thiostrepton-resistant clones were isolated. After veriﬁcation of the recombination event by Southern blot analysis ( Fig. 2B), the mutant strain was tested for naphthocyclinone production on agar plates. In contrast to the wild-type, which excretes a dark red–brown pigment into the medium, the mutant did not produce this typical compound. Two of the major products synthesized by the wild-type, as judged from HPLC proﬁles (not shown), were isolated, puriﬁed and the elucidated by NMR analysis chemical ( Fig. 3A). One be compound was a-naphthocyclinone, and a second major product was identiﬁed as demethyl-a-naphthocyclinone (a-naphtho- cyclinone acid ) ( Krone et al., 1982). HPLC analysis of agar extracts conﬁrmed that, in contrast to the wild- type, the mutant strain made no detectable naphthocycli- nones (not shown). This indicates that the isolated polyketide cluster is the only one in S. arenae that is responsible for naphthocyclinone biosynthesis.

3.4. Heterologous expression of the S. arenae polyketide genes The genes isolated from S. arenae were expressed in S. coelicolor CH999 using a host–vector system devel- oped by McDaniel et al., 1993 to verify their proposed functions. Various combinations of the genes from diVerent polyketide clusters with genes from the naph- thocyclinone cluster were constructed. The S. arenae PKS genes (ncnABC ) were coexpressed with the ketore- ductase from the actinorhodin cluster (pETR381), lead- ing to the synthesis of two major compounds [mutactin and dehydromutactin ( Fig. 3B); McDaniel et al., 1994]. Expression of the S. arenae PKS genes alone (pETR361) led to the formation of SEK4 ( Fu et al., 1994) and the dehydrated form of SEK4, which was designated as B26 ( Fig. 3C ). All these compounds were puriﬁed and ana- lyzed by NMR. Mutactin, dehydromutactin and SEK4 were already described to be produced by the minimal polyketide synthase from the S. coelicolor actinorhodin cluster, whereas the compound B26 seems to be a novel compound. B26 was not observed with S. coelicolor CH999/pSEK4, which was extracted in the same way as S. coelicolor CH999/pETR361. The structure of naphthocyclinone points to the possible involvement of an O-methyltransferase in bio- synthesis of this polyketide. However, no hybridization signal was observed with a dnrK speciﬁc probe, the O- methyltransferase gene from S. peucetius (Madduri and Hutchinson, 1995). Possible reasons might be that these O-methyltransferase genes are too diverse or that the isolated fragment does not contain the entire naphtho- cyclinone cluster and that the O-methyltransferase gene is not contained within the cloned fragment. The stop codon of ncnA overlaps with the start codon of ncnB (GTG), leading to a translational coupling of ketosyn- thase and chain length factor, which is often found within the PKS genes. This translational coupling proba- bly ensures that both enzymes are synthesized in equi- molar amounts. (DLGYDSLALMETAARI ), common for a variety of bacterial acyl carrier proteins ( Fernandez-Moreno et al., 1992), could be identiﬁed at position 36–51 in the deduced peptide sequence of 86 aa. Overlapping with the stop codon of ncnC is the start codon, GTG, of the fourth open reading frame (ncnD), which codes for a bifunctional cyclase/dehydrase. Separated by approxi- mately 8 kb from the PKS genes, a DNA fragment hybridizing with an actIV probe (encoding the actinor- hodin cyclase) was identiﬁed. Two divergently tran- scribed open reading frames (ncnE, ncnR) were identiﬁed on this fragment, encoding a cyclase and a putative regulatory protein, respectively. The distance between ncnE and the polyketide synthase genes suggests that they are organized in diVerent transcriptional units, similar to the daunorubicin cluster from S. peucetius where the cyclase gene is located 1.3 kb upstream of the PKS genes (Grimm et al., 1994). The presented data on the genetic organization of the naphthocyclinone polyke- tide synthase genes from S. arenae show that it is a typical type-II polyketide gene cluster where the PKS genes are arranged in one transcriptional unit, although the upstream location of ncnE encoding the cyclase is unusual but not unique, as seen from the daunorubicin cluster from S. peucetius.

the naphthocyclinone polyketide synthase, the cyclase and aromatase from S. arenae have been conﬁrmed by functional expression of these genes in combination with genes from other polyketide gene clusters. Whereas the PKS and cyclase exhibited the same enzymatic activity as the correspond- ing proteins from the actinorhodin pathway, the S. arenae aromatase seems to have had a broader substrate range than the act aromatase. NcnD acts not only on C-16 backbones but also on C-20 cores, as shown by coexpression of ncnD with the tcm PKS and the act ketoreductase, leading to the production of a novel compound, P-517, which is an aromatized form of RM20b ( Khosla et al., 1992). This makes the S. arenae aromatase a potential candidate for the production of novel recombinant polyketides. We thank Heidi Ernst for excellent technical assis- tance and DNA sequencing.
